## Behavioral Graph Matching for Fast Malware Classification

Malware classification is an essential task in cybersecurity, as it allows for the identification and mitigation
of malicious software. Research has proposed a fast malware classification technique based on automated
behavioral graph matching [5]. This approach leverages the behavioral characteristics of malware to
classify and detect potential threats. By incorporating behavioral analysis into malware classification,
researchers can enhance the effectiveness of cybersecurity systems and improve their ability to detect and
mitigate cyber threats.

## Human Factors in Cybersecurity

The role of human factors in cybersecurity has gained significant attention in recent years. Research has
demonstrated the link between internet addiction, impulsivity, attitudes towards cybersecurity, and risky
cybersecurity behaviors [12]. Understanding these behavioral aspects can help develop targeted interventions and training programs to improve cybersecurity practices. Additionally, incorporating human
factors and ergonomics principles in the design of cybersecurity systems can enhance their usability and
effectiveness [18]. By considering human factors, such as cognitive abilities, limitations, and preferences,
researchers can design cybersecurity systems that are intuitive, user-friendly, and promote secure behavior.

## Industrial Critical Infrastructure and Cybersecurity

The industrial critical infrastructure sector faces numerous cybersecurity challenges. Research has
highlighted the need to address cybersecurity issues in manufacturing and other industrial sectors [8].
Understanding the unique challenges and vulnerabilities of industrial critical infrastructure can inform
the development of tailored cybersecurity strategies. Future research should focus on identifying and
mitigating the specific cybersecurity threats faced by the industrial sector and developing strategies to
enhance the resilience and security of critical infrastructure systems.

## Artificial Intelligence in Cybersecurity

Artificial intelligence (AI) has emerged as a promising tool in the field of cybersecurity. Research has
explored the use of AI methods for detecting and preventing cybersecurity attacks [11]. Federated learning,
a decentralized AI approach, has shown potential for enhancing cybersecurity [11]. This approach allows
for collaborative learning across distributed devices while preserving data privacy. Further research is
needed to explore the concepts, challenges, and future directions of using AI, including federated learning,
in cybersecurity.

## Prevention of Phishing Attacks Using AI-Based Cybersecurity Awareness Training

Phishing attacks pose a significant threat to information security. Research has investigated the use of
AI-based cybersecurity awareness training to prevent phishing attacks [13]. This approach leverages AI
2 / 5
